lesson-1.title: Self-Discipline
lesson-1.storyText: Sidian stood before a towering bookshelf as an arcana-etched tome floated to him, its pages flipping open with a faint glow. The librarian’s disembodied voice began recounting the ancient battles—a time when the lands were ruled by endless war. Armies clashed without end, their leaders consumed by greed and vengeance. There was no unity, only fractured factions vying for fleeting power, staining the earth with blood. Sidian absorbed the weight of the past, understanding how deeply conflict had shaped Tetraea’s fractured present.

panel-1.panelText: Reflection allows us to review our past thoughts, feelings, and actions, while discipline focuses on controlling them in real-time. Discipline isn’t about punishment—it’s about learning. When we practice self-discipline, we take on the role of our own teacher, guiding ourselves toward growth and mastery.

panel-2.panelText: Self-discipline goes hand in hand with the choices we make every day. These choices shape our habits and determine our path forward. We’ll dive deeper into the connection between discipline and decision-making in a future lesson.

panel-3.panelText: Integrity is deeply tied to self-discipline. It reflects who you are when no one else is around, showing your true character. By practicing discipline and integrity, you create a foundation of trust, respect, and authenticity in both yourself and others.

panel-4.panelText: Life is full of small tasks that may not feel exciting but are necessary for growth. Discipline helps us tackle these moments with focus and determination. By managing your emotions, thoughts, and actions, you align yourself with your goals and build the life you want.

lesson-2.title: Focus
lesson-2.storyText: A second tome floated forward, its cover dark and pulsing with a faint, ominous glow. As Sidian opened it, the library seemed to dim, the description of the Abyss pouring out like a void. The librarian’s voice painted a grim picture of an infinite, chaotic realm where lost souls drifted endlessly. The Abyss was a prison of despair, a plane beyond life, light, and escape. Sidian felt a shiver as the weight of its existence settled over him, a reminder of the stakes tied to failure.

panel-1.panelText: Focus in chess means tuning out distractions and fully engaging with the board. A wandering mind or split attention can lead to missed opportunities or costly mistakes. Similarly, in life, focus requires ignoring the noise—be it social media, unnecessary tasks, or external pressures—and concentrating on what truly matters. Chess teaches us that success comes not from doing everything but from dedicating ourselves fully to the most important task at hand.

panel-2.panelText: In chess, focus means identifying the key threats and opportunities and prioritizing them over secondary concerns. Not every pawn push or piece move is equally important. In life, this translates to honing in on the tasks and goals that have the greatest impact. Focus helps us avoid getting bogged down by trivial matters, ensuring that our time and energy go toward what will move us forward.

panel-3.panelText: Focus isn’t just about being attentive—it’s about going deep. In chess, mastering focus involves dedicating yourself to deep calculation, envisioning multiple moves ahead, and understanding the nuances of a position. In life, this is often referred to as “deep work”: immersing yourself in meaningful, high-impact tasks without interruption. Chess reminds us that surface-level engagement rarely leads to mastery, while focused effort produces excellence.

panel-4.panelText: Maintaining focus in a long chess game requires mental stamina. Fatigue can erode focus, leading to errors in critical moments. Life’s challenges often demand this same resilience. By training our ability to focus, we strengthen our capacity to stay sharp under pressure and remain effective even when the going gets tough. Chess demonstrates that the ability to focus is as much about discipline and endurance as it is about mental clarity.

lesson-3.title: The Draw
lesson-3.nodeText: The endgame scenario that may or may not be in your favor.
lesson-3.storyText: The next tome radiated faint lines of light forming angular patterns across its surface. As Sidian read, the librarian explained the pentagrams—ancient seals created to bind great power. Over time, they became tools of judgment, marking the fates of those defeated in the Tactorius Games. To lose under a pentagram was to be cast into the Abyss, body and soul, ensuring no return. Sidian clenched his fists, realizing how deeply the games were tied to fear and finality.

panel-1.panelText: Draws are a game-ending scenario where both sides attain half a point. One way is for a player to offer a draw and the opponent can choose to agree or play on. There are four on-board types of draws.

panel-2.panelText: Stalemate: when it is a player’s turn and has no legal moves to play and is not in check.

panel-3.panelText: Repetition: when the same on-board position occurs three times.

panel-4.panelText: Repetition: when the same on-board position occurs three times.

panel-10.panelText: Repetition: when the same on-board position occurs three times.

panel-11.panelText: This particular repitition is an example of the tactic:  perpetual check. White is winning and shouldn't have made the draw, but there are other scenarios where the losing side might be able to force a repitition to save the game and half point.

panel-12.panelText: Insufficient material: if enough material is traded off, then there might not be enough to deliver a checkmate.

panel-13.panelText: The last is the 50-move rule. If 50 moves go by without a Pawn move or a capture move, then each player gets the half point.

lesson-4.title: The Principles
lesson-4.nodeText: If you want to hold your own through a full game, keep in mind these conventions when deciding on your moves.
lesson-4.storyText: A larger, heavier tome arrived, its pages gilded with faintly shimmering symbols of unity. Sidian learned how exhaustion from the ancient battles eventually forced the warring factions into uneasy alliances. These alliances gave rise to the cities of Tetraea, with Axioms emerging as stabilizing forces to channel the chaos of arcana. Yet even as the wars ended, the mistrust and scars they left behind became the foundation for Tetraea’s fractured state.

panel-1.panelText: Keep in mind that some of the chess rule of thumbs like these are subjective and depends on what position you are in

panel-2.panelText: Games typically start with a Pawn move. A Pawn duo near the center is optimal, just enough to let your pieces into the fight. Make minimum Pawn moves as to not show your hand so quick.

panel-3.panelText: Development: move your pieces toward the center of the board. Minor pieces: Knights first, then Bishops. Careful with your Queen placement. It’s valuable so you want to make sure it doesn’t get kicked around by less-expensive pieces. Once you connect your Rooks and they can see each other, you’ll know you’ve done a good job with this principle. In about the first 10 moves, it is recommended that you move each of your pieces only once.

panel-4.panelText: Center Control: placing your pieces in the center is good, but even better is keeping an influence on the center. This is the dream setup for white. A Pawn duo, and pieces attacking the center. Keep in mind that a piece does not control the square that it occupies, it will need support.

panel-5.panelText: King Safety: Let’s cover castling. The path must be clear between your King and Rook. If you move your King or the respective Rook then you lose the right to castle. Take note of the following sequence.

panel-6.panelText: The King moves right (or left for queenside) two squares.

panel-7.panelText: The Rook hops over the King to the next square.

panel-8.panelText: Castle early. This gets your King out of the center of the board and brings your Rook into the action. An important note here: be mindful about moving the Pawns in front of the side you plan to castle on, it might not be a good idea. We will cover more on Pawn weaknesses later on.

lesson-5.title: Minor Pieces I
lesson-5.nodeText: Learn about the Bishop and Equus pieces. They aren't the strongest, but they are important.
lesson-5.storyText: A slim but intricate tome drifted to Sidian, its cover resembling interwoven threads of light. The librarian recounted the Hexweavers’ intervention at the height of the ancient wars. These enigmatic multiversal beings wove reality itself, using their power to bind the warring factions and establish the first pentagrams to stabilize the multiverse. The Hexweavers vanished after their task, leaving only their seals and whispered legends, but their influence shaped the laws of Tetraea that still endured.

panel-1.panelText: Both Knights and Bishops weigh in at about 3 points each. This a loose measurement as the point values differ based on the position on the board. Knights are favored in more ‘closed’, pawn-locked positions. Bishops on the other hand perform better in open positions, where more pawns have been traded off.

panel-2.panelText: With less research on the Zebra and Unicorn, they may tend to operate similar to the Knight. All three of them don’t have that full-length scope that the Bishop has, but a more close range advantage with the ability to maneuver static pawn structures.

panel-3.panelText: The drawback on the Bishop becomes readily apparent with a closer glance at the board. It is only subject to one color complex (as is the Zebra). They can’t go to every square like a lot of other pieces but they make up for this by exerting a strong presence on the color they live on.

panel-4.panelText: The big advantage each player starts out with is having two Bishops (one for each color), and now in some cases two Zebras. A potential side quest or plan for any match you play is hold onto this pair and you will have good luck on both color complexes, the full board.

panel-5.panelText: Consider the Bishop a bit further. Take a look at this position. One of these Bishops is considered ‘good’ and the other ‘bad’, can you guess which is which?

panel-6.panelText: Why is this? Take a look at the Pawn structure. The Pawns in the center are mainly on light squares. This means for the light-squared Bishop that it can’t move anywhere. It is not of use.

panel-7.panelText: New side quest (if you so choose): figure out which Bishops of you and your opponent are good and bad. See if you can perform some captures (trading) where you keep your good Bishop and your opponent keeps their bad Bishop.

panel-8.panelText: One last point on Bishops: this dark-squared Bishop is on the same square as all the center Pawns, but it’s in front of the chain of Pawns. It is an ‘active’ Bishop and is not affected by it’s bad Bishop trait.

lesson-6.title: Minor Pieces II
lesson-6.nodeText: Attain more details about the Bishop and Equus pieces.
lesson-6.storyText: A spectral tome appeared, its pages flickering like distant constellations. As Sidian studied it, the librarian recounted the tale of Tejeduras, the wrathful demigod and ancient ghostly creator tied to the fabric of the multiverse. Tejeduras was said to have crafted the first arcana, weaving it into constructs and entities that laid the foundation for all magic in Tetraea. Though revered for this creation, his wrath stemmed from betrayal by those who sought to misuse his gifts, leading to his retreat into the deepest folds of the multiverse. Sidian felt a chill as he realized that the whispers of Tejeduras’ influence still lingered, shaping the arcana that fueled Tetraea’s fragile balance.

panel-1.panelText: Consider the Knight: Placed on the rim, it’s activity is dim. (next) Place it in the center? You’re good to go. On the edge it attacks two squares, in the center it attacks eight. This is analogous to good and bad bishops. How many points do you think it’s worth in either position?

panel-2.panelText: A useful motif for minor pieces is the Pawn blockade. The Pawn on e4 is passed and wants to promote. With our Knight standing guard in front of it that won’t be happening any time soon. A very useful spot as the Knight has no trouble with moving away if needed in an attack or defense.

panel-3.panelText: Another motif you will see often is the outpost. This Knight is nested in the opponents territory, controlling key squares in Black’s weak position. While either side maintains an 'advanced support point’ like we have here, they will have a considerable advantage. If captured, it can be replaced by another piece or Pawn.

panel-4.panelText: The Steinitz Rule. To reiterate, you want advanced support points… specifically for your Knights. Think ahead here, what prospective square do you think this black Knight might be looking to land on some turn?

panel-5.panelText: In this situation, it’s b5 and d5. Maybe not in every instance, but Steinitz Rule here states to take away the advanced (support) point for Knights. (next) Pushing a Pawn forward like this does just that.

panel-6.panelText: In this situation, it’s b5 and d5. Maybe not in every instance, but Steinitz Rule here states to take away the advanced (support) point for Knights. Pushing a Pawn forward like this does just that.

panel-7.panelText: Similar to the open and closed position tradeoff, the Bishop vs Knight (Zebra and Unicorn for this as well) have certain advantages in different Pawn endgames.

panel-8.panelText: When there are Pawns on both sides of the board, the Bishop has the agility to move to either side of the board to guard or attack Pawns. The close-proximity attackers do not have this luxury.

panel-9.panelText: On the other hand, The Equus pieces operate well in endgames where there are only Pawns on one side the board. They excel here more than the Bishop because they have access to more squares.

panel-10.panelText: The interplay between the minor pieces play an important role in the middlegame. They each hold their own built in advantages and disadvantages. Foster them with care, plan on which ones to keep and trade off based on the position. Each hold the ability to create tactical advantages which we'll cover next.

lesson-7.title: Tactics I
lesson-7.nodeText: Learn about novice-level tactics and how to spot them.
lesson-7.storyText: The final tome, radiating a kaleidoscope of colors, opened before Sidian, its pages brimming with flowing script and diagrams. The librarian detailed arcana as the essence of life and reality, categorized into elemental, dimensional, and spectral types. Forbidden arcana, tied to the Abyss and pentagrams, were powerful but dangerous, capable of warping existence itself. Sidian began to grasp the magnitude of arcana’s potential, understanding both its wonders and its dangers as he prepared for the trials ahead.

panel-1.panelText: Tactics, they are the short-term advantages that gain you material or an edge in a sharp attack. Finding these patterns and acting upon them swiftly can make or break your match to a win or loss.

panel-2.panelText: Not strictly a tactic, but a motif to look out for is pieces that are undefended or poorly defended. A hanging piece (undefended) is free material, a decisive advantage. The tactic to assert when a piece is poorly defended (more attackers than defenders) is called removing the defender. (next) Here we see white is ‘undermining’ black’s center. If black takes, it removes the defender of the black Knight and winning white a material advantage.

panel-3.panelText: Not strictly a tactic, but a motif to look out for is pieces that are undefended or poorly defended. A hanging piece (undefended) is free material, a decisive advantage. The tactic to assert when a piece is poorly defended (1 maybe 2 defenders) is called removing the defender. (next) Here we see white is ‘undermining’ black’s center. If black takes, it’s removes the defender of the black Knight and winning white a material advantage.

panel-4.panelText: There are more ways to remove the defender that we will discuss later. Any tactic we mention in this type of lesson are only relevant when there are undefended pieces, poorly defended pieces, and when you can check an opposing, unsafe King (see pattern recognition).

panel-5.panelText: There are more ways to remove the defender that we will discuss later. Any tactic we mention in this type of lesson are only relevant when there are undefended pieces, poorly defended pieces, and when you can check an opposing, unsafe King (see pattern recognition).

panel-6.panelText: There are more ways to remove the defender that we will discuss later. Any tactic we mention in this type of lesson are only relevant when there are undefended pieces, poorly defended pieces, and when you can check an opposing, unsafe King (see pattern recognition).

panel-7.panelText: There are more ways to remove the defender that we will discuss later. Any tactic we mention in this type of lesson are only relevant when there are undefended pieces, poorly defended pieces, and when you can check an opposing, unsafe King (see pattern recognition).

panel-8.panelText: The arguably most important tactic is the fork. A type of double attack where one piece attacks two pieces. Any piece can do this, but is a specialty of the Knight. With it’s reach to odd surrounding squares, it has a good chance of catching undefended pieces or a checked King off guard.

panel-9.panelText: Another tactical staple is called the pin. It is only realized on a slider piece (Rook or Bishop movement patterns). This happens when a slider piece aligns with two hostile pieces. It directly attacks a lower value piece, with a higher value piece indirectly attacked behind the first piece.

panel-10.panelText: Here are two examples. The first example is known as an ‘absolute’ pin. Black cannot move the Rook, it is illegal because it puts the Black King in check. The second example is a relative pin. Here black needs to move the Knight because it is undefended, but once it does, we will capture the Rook and win material.

panel-11.panelText: Here are two examples. The first example is known as an ‘absolute’ pin. Black cannot move the Rook, it is illegal because it puts the Black King in check. The second example is a relative pin. Here black need to move the Knight because it is undefended, but once it does, well capture the Rook and win material.

panel-12.panelText: A similar tactic is called the skewer. It works exactly like the pin, except the higher-valued piece is being directly attacked. Here black King is skewered to the Queen. The King is worth the game, the Queen is worth less than that. Once black moves out of check, we take the Queen.

panel-13.panelText: They say “pin it to win it”. When you have an opponent's piece in a pin you should put pressure on it when you can. Attacking with a Pawn can be decisive but if it’s only pieces, try to add pressure then convert from dynamic to static advantage.

panel-14.panelText: Be on the lookout for these rules and patterns in your matches. They are there lurking in some positions, you just need to find them!

temple-1.title: Temple of Skewers I
temple-1.storyText: The air shifted as Sidian entered Raven’s Den, a dimly lit temple cloaked in perpetual twilight. A raven perched atop a jagged column at the entrance, its eyes gleaming with intelligence and mischief. It cawed sharply and fluttered into the corridor ahead, beckoning him to follow. As Sidian stepped through, the entrance behind him dissolved, replaced by an endless hallway lined with doors. The raven lingered just ahead, offering cryptic remarks that felt more mocking than helpful, its presence both a guide and a challenge.

temple-2.title: Temple of Skewers II
temple-2.storyText: The raven flitted down the corridor, landing near a heavy stone door and tilting its head as if to encourage Sidian forward. Trusting the hint, Sidian pushed open the door, revealing only a blank stone wall on the other side. The air grew heavy with silence, broken only by the raven’s soft cackle as it disappeared down another corridor. Frustrated, Sidian retraced his steps, the endless doors feeling more oppressive with every turn.

temple-3.title: Temple of Forks I
temple-3.storyText: Sidian pressed his hand against the cold stone door, the weight of it groaning as it swung open. Beyond lay a dimly lit hallway stretching forward before splitting into two paths, each shrouded in shadow. The left fork flickered faintly with a soft blue light emanating from an unseen source, while the right remained dark and uninviting, its air heavy with an oppressive stillness. The raven landed on a nearby ledge, tilting its head as if amused, its cryptic caw echoing through the space. Sidian hesitated, feeling the pull of both paths, uncertain whether the raven’s presence was a warning or an invitation to trust his instincts.

temple-4.title: Temple of Forks II
temple-4.storyText: The raven perched atop another doorway, its beady eyes watching as it spoke in riddles, hinting at a correct path. Sidian, suspicious of its intentions, chose to ignore the advice and opened a door at random. The room beyond was empty, its silence ringing with futility. As he turned, the corridor behind him had shifted, the way back now obscured. The raven reappeared, its mocking cry echoing through the maze as Sidian realized he had wasted precious time on mistrust.

temple-5.title: Temple of Pins I
temple-5.storyText: After wandering aimlessly, Sidian followed the raven into a hidden chamber deep within the maze. At the center stood a pedestal, atop which rested a shimmering arcana pulsing with faint light. The raven circled the room, offering riddles about focus and calculation. As Sidian reached for the arcana, it filled him with a surge of energy, granting fleeting visions of possible futures. The raven cawed approvingly and vanished into the shadows, leaving Sidian with newfound clarity to navigate the temple.

temple-6.title: Temple of Pins II
temple-6.storyText: With the future sight arcana, Sidian began to anticipate the outcomes of each door, visualizing paths before committing to them. The raven returned, sometimes offering misleading riddles, other times cryptic encouragement, but Sidian tuned out its distractions, trusting his own focus and the power of the arcana. Door by door, he moved with purpose, the labyrinth’s oppressive weight lifting as the correct path revealed itself. At last, he stepped through the final door, emerging into the open air, the raven’s caw fading into the distance as the temple stood silent behind him.

mission-1.title: A Throne for the Taking
mission-1.nodeText: Get your King to the center to win or defeat your opponent normally.
mission-1.storyText: The dimly lit tavern buzzed with hushed conversation as Sidian approached a grizzled hunter nursing a half-empty tankard. The hunter recounted the strange disappearances plaguing Thornreach—travelers vanishing without a trace, their camps eerily untouched save for faint scorch marks etched into the ground. As the hunter leaned closer, his voice dropped to a whisper, and he mentioned an ancient name: Baelgorath. The sorcerer’s curse, he claimed, was the source of the disappearances, spreading like a sickness through the forest. Winning a game of cards against the hunter, Sidian earned a few coins and a warning not to stray too far into the shadows of Thornreach.

mission-2.title: Conversion Bias
mission-2.storyText: Later that night, Sidian met another hunter who shared tales of the Ephilates, spectral figures cursed to wander Thornshade. Their souls, stolen by Baelgorath’s dark magic, were bound to the forest, endlessly searching for more to trap in their cursed state. The hunter described the spirits’ eerie stillness, their silent forms concealing the power to ensnare the living with spectral chains. After losing a few coins in a dice game, Sidian left the tavern with more questions than answers, the looming presence of Baelgorath casting a shadow over everything he had learned.

mission-3.title: A Matter of Technique
mission-3.storyText: Sidian climbed the spiraling staircase of the clocktower, the rhythmic ticking reverberating through the massive structure. At the summit, he found the Watchmaker, an enigmatic figure cloaked in metallic robes, their hands carefully adjusting the intricate mechanisms of the central gear. Without turning, the Watchmaker spoke, their voice calm yet unsettling, weaving cryptic remarks about the fragility of time and the delicate balance Sidian’s actions threatened to unravel. Amid their musings, they mentioned the Mirror Temple, a place west of Thornshade that existed only in whispers—a rumored multiverse portal connecting realms beyond comprehension.

mission-4.title: Team Jousting
mission-4.storyText: As the conversation lingered, the Watchmaker’s tone shifted, hinting at another destination—Raven’s Den. Unlike the Mirror Temple, which bridged dimensions, Raven’s Den was a mystical sanctuary said to house a rare form of magic unlike anything in Tetraea. The Watchmaker warned that Raven’s Den was as dangerous as it was powerful, its magic capable of reshaping perception itself. Turning back to their work, the Watchmaker dismissed Sidian with a final cryptic comment, leaving him to descend the clocktower, the weight of their revelations pressing heavily on his thoughts.

mission-5.title: Two Way Haunt

diagWinLose.defeat: The Ephilate’s summoning circle erupted, spectral chains pulling Sidian into its glowing core. The ground fractured beneath him as the portal to the Abyss opened wide, its endless void swallowing him whole. As he fell, the oppressive darkness closed in, and distant chanting echoed around him, a haunting chorus from the satanic church that grew louder with each passing moment, marking his descent into eternal oblivion.

mission-5.storyText: Venturing deeper into Thornreach, Sidian encountered his first Ephilate—a spectral figure shrouded in an eerie stillness. It sat motionless, its hollow eyes fixed on him, emitting a faint hum that seemed to pull at his very essence. As Sidian approached, the Ephilate’s arcana flared, and spectral chains erupted from the ground, forcing him to phase and counterattack with precision. With a final blow, the Ephilate dissolved into the shadows, but the oppressive energy in the air remained.

mission-6.title: Flank Haunt

diagWinLose.defeat: The Ephilate’s summoning circle erupted, spectral chains pulling Sidian into its glowing core. The ground fractured beneath him as the portal to the Abyss opened wide, its endless void swallowing him whole. As he fell, the oppressive darkness closed in, and distant chanting echoed around him, a haunting chorus from the satanic church that grew louder with each passing moment, marking his descent into eternal oblivion.

mission-6.storyText: Deeper into the shadowed expanse of Thornreach, Sidian encountered a second Ephilate, its spectral form still and unyielding as it blocked his path. Without warning, the creature raised its ghostly hands, weaving intricate patterns of arcana into the air. The ground beneath Sidian erupted into a glowing summoning circle, spectral chains lashing out to bind him before he could react. Stripped of his spectre abilities, he struggled in vain as the circle pulsed with dark energy, dragging him through a twisting veil of dimensions. When the light faded, he found himself in the heart of the satanic church, surrounded by chanting priests and under the cold, piercing gaze of Baelgorath, his captor and tormentor.

mission-7.title: Storm on the Safari

diagWinLose.defeat: The summoning circle flared with unnatural light, and Sidian, restrained by Baelgorath’s arcane chains, was dragged into its center. The portal roared open, revealing towering cross-dimensional beings with piercing eyes and twisted forms. Baelgorath’s voice echoed with triumph as he declared Sidian the final offering. The beings’ claws reached through the portal, pulling Sidian into their realm as the circle’s glow faded, leaving behind only silence and Baelgorath’s dark laughter.

mission-7.storyText: Sidian awoke bound in spectral chains, the cold, damp air of the satanic church pressing down like a shroud. The cathedral’s towering walls glowed faintly with arcane runes, their light pulsing in rhythm with the chants of robed priests encircling him. At the center of the grand hall, Baelgorath stood within a massive summoning circle, his form imposing and his voice commanding. He addressed his followers, detailing his dark triumph—the curse he had unleashed upon Thornshade and Gravespine. By corrupting the lands, he had siphoned their life force into the summoning circle, preparing to open a portal to the Abyss that would solidify his dominion over Tetraea.

mission-8.title: All Hands on Deck

diagWinLose.victory: Sidian channeled the arcana’s power, shattering Baelgorath’s defenses and redirecting the summoning circle’s energy. The portal to the Abyss flared, its pull reversing onto Baelgorath. The sorcerer’s defiant screams faded as he was dragged into the void. The portal closed, leaving Sidian victorious amidst the ruins, the chamber finally silent.
diagWinLose.defeat: The summoning circle flared with unnatural light, and Sidian, restrained by Baelgorath’s arcane chains, was dragged into its center. The portal roared open, revealing towering cross-dimensional beings with piercing eyes and twisted forms. Baelgorath’s voice echoed with triumph as he declared Sidian the final offering. The beings’ claws reached through the portal, pulling Sidian into their realm as the circle’s glow faded, leaving behind only silence and Baelgorath’s dark laughter.

mission-8.storyText: The summoning circle erupted in chaos as Sidian shattered its arcane flow, sending cracks rippling across the cathedral floor. Baelgorath sneered, his escape into the Abyss interrupted as he turned his full attention to Sidian. With a wave of his hand, the sorcerer unleashed waves of abyssal energy, summoning spectral constructs to overwhelm him. The priests scattered, their chants silenced by the raw power now coursing through the chamber. Sidian steadied himself, channeling the arcana he had mastered to counter Baelgorath’s relentless onslaught. The air thickened with the clash of energies, every strike bringing the two closer to the inevitable confrontation at the center of the shattered circle.

mission-11.nodeText: Anatoly Karpov vs Garry Kasparov: World Championship Match (1985)
